      <div class="msgContentFrame">I think most people look at Gladiator the wrong way. <br /> <br />First, ask yourself, what is the intended role of the job &quot;Gladiator&quot; in this game? Gladiators are locked into using only swords and daggers and given the option to use a shield in the offhand.  The abilities that Gladiators gain focus on using their blades to do special attacks, to generate enmity, to reduce enimty loss, to increase their personal defenses, and to cover allies by throwing their body between them and their attacker.  And that's just using a blade without a shield.  WITH a shield, Gladiators eventually gain the ability to keep their Guard up longer (i.e. Self-Preservation) and the ability to retaliate after a shield block (i.e. Phalanx).  Interesting enough, Shield skill is independent of the other Disciples, but if you can wield a shield in your offhand and you can block with it and you can get skill with it. The abilities gained from shield skill such as Aegis Boon and Shield Bash only help to further increase a Gladiator's survivability in combat. <br /> <br />All this screams, at least to me, that Gladiators are tanks.  Combined with the other job abilities such as Cures from Conjurer or even Taunt from Pugilist for an additional provoking ability, Gladiators can customize themselves in a variety of ways to tank, survive, and hold hate (most of the time). <br /> <br />Gladiators remind me much of my experiences with FF11, in which I loved playing Paladin. Gladiator shares many of the same hardships I faced back in my days on FF11 where Paladins solo'd very slowly because they were balanced to survive and have high defense versus high offense.  Marauders on the other hand, remind me much of Warriors in FF11 and they both also had no problem in dishing out the pain in spades. But in a pinch, Marauders (and Warriors in FF11 for that matter) can tank too. I think that SquarEnix carefully thought how they would balance out Gladiator and Marauder so one wouldn't outshine the other when it came to what they were best at, but leaving the flexibility there for when one needs to do the other's job in a pinch. <br /> <br />I'm pretty sure that with a little tweaking and some fore thought, one can customize a Gladiator to be a fairly good Damage Dealer.  And there is nothing wrong with that either. Maybe early on, that's not so viable, but this game is very complex and is still new.  I agree that there are some inherent flaws preventing this game from being more enjoyable such as the lag between inputs into the User Interface.  Oh, how I hate missing the timing on a critical Cure and dying as a result from it. Regardless, I just want to reiterate that I don't think Gladiator is Underpowered if you play on it's strong points.<div class="msgSig"><div class="msgSigBar sm">----------------------------</div>Consciousness - That annoying time between naps.</div></div>
